%I A395131 #12 Apr 19 2026 19:50:05
%S A395131 36967783,36967842,36969142,36973760,36979528,36961052,36966895,
%T A395131 36972157,36970838,36964103
%N A395131 Number of occurrences of digit n in 9^9^9.
%C A395131 In 1979, Joseph Madachy predicted in Madachy's Mathematical Recreations that the 369693100 digits of 9^9^9 "would almost guarantee that the number never will be fully evaluated." Now any home computer can calculate it in seconds.
%C A395131 9^9^9 = 3^774840978, so a surplus of 3s in the digit distribution might at first glance be expected. In fact, each digit count differs by less than 0.03% from the mean.
%C A395131 At 12 digits per inch (about 4.7 per cm), the decimal expansion of 9^9^9 printed on a paper tape would exceed 486 miles (782 km).
%D A395131 J. S. Madachy, Madachy's Mathematical Recreations, Dover Publications, New York, 1979, p. 176.
%H A395131 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Madachy">Joseph Madachy</a>.
%e A395131 a(8)=36970838 because the digit 8 appears 36970838 times in 9^9^9.
%t A395131 Last/@Sort[Tally[IntegerDigits[9^9^9]]]
%t A395131 (* 9^9^9 takes 6 seconds; IntegerDigits 120 seconds; Tally 1 second *)
%Y A395131 Cf. A054382, A241298, A002488.
%K A395131 nonn,base,fini,full,new
%O A395131 0,1
%A A395131 _David Dewan_, Apr 12 2026
